    <h1>Why did Denmark shift its immigration policy?</h1>
    <p class="intro">Since 2001, Denmark has adopted one of Europe's most restrictive immigration and integration policy frameworks. This page presents the official statistical data and a factual chronology of legislative changes, without editorial commentary.</p>
    <div class="lang-switch"><a href="/faq/denmark-policy-shift/">🌐 日本語版</a></div>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>Official statistical context</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Indicator</th>
          <th>Figure</th>
          <th>Source</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Net fiscal cost of immigration</td>
          <td>−16 billion DKK/year</td>
          <td><a href="https://www.fm.dk" rel="noopener">Finansministeriet 2023</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Employment rate gap (immigrants vs. native-born)</td>
          <td>−14.5 percentage points (2023)</td>
          <td><a href="https://www.dst.dk" rel="noopener">Danmarks Statistik (DST) 2023</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Crime rate index</td>
          <td>2.6× (native-born = 1)</td>
          <td><a href="https://www.dst.dk" rel="noopener">Danmarks Statistik (DST)</a></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Policy chronology (2001–2023)</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Date</th>
          <th>Government</th>
          <th>Key measure</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>2001</td>
          <td>Centre-right coalition (Venstre + DPP support)</td>
          <td>Substantial restriction of immigration and asylum rules. Strengthened integration requirements.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2002</td>
          <td>Same</td>
          <td>Family reunification restrictions ("24-year rule"). Mandatory integration contract.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2010s</td>
          <td>Various governments</td>
          <td>Introduction of points system. Reduction of settlement benefits ("start-help" scheme).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2018</td>
          <td>Centre-right coalition</td>
          <td>"Ghetto Act" (ghettoloven): policy to dismantle ethnically concentrated public housing areas.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2019</td>
          <td>Social Democratic government (Mette Frederiksen)</td>
          <td>Restrictive immigration policy maintained and continued. "Zero refugee" target announced.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2002–2023</td>
          <td>Multiple governments</td>
          <td>Gradual tightening of integration requirements, mandatory language and civic tests, stricter permanent residence criteria.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Methodological limits</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Aggregation scope:</strong> DST's "immigrant background" category mixes EU labour migrants, skilled workers, refugees, and family reunification migrants. The fiscal burden is concentrated in the refugee/family reunification segment but may not be separated in aggregate statistics.</li>
      <li><strong>Crime index controls:</strong> DST's crime index applies only partial controls for age and socioeconomic status. Raw figures may overstate the gap.</li>
      <li><strong>Policy effect measurement:</strong> The causal effects of post-2001 policy changes (improvement or deterioration in integration outcomes) cannot be measured without a credible counterfactual.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this data does not show</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The statistical figures did not mechanically cause the political decisions. Public opinion, specific events (terrorist attacks, high-profile crimes), and political competition (the rise of the Danish People's Party) also shaped policy formation. Causality cannot be established from statistics alone.</li>
      <li>Whether Danish policy has "succeeded" or "failed" cannot be derived from the statistics. The evaluation depends on which indicators are prioritised: integration rates, fiscal balance, social cohesion, or human rights considerations.</li>
      <li>The Social Democratic Party's adoption of restrictive immigration policy does not prove the policy's effectiveness; it also reflects electoral competition dynamics.</li>
      <li>The effects of specific measures such as the Ghetto Act cannot be assessed without follow-up evaluation studies post-implementation.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Primary sources</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Finansministeriet (2023). <em>Indvandreres nettobidrag til de offentlige finanser</em>. <a href="https://www.fm.dk" rel="noopener">www.fm.dk</a></li>
      <li>Danmarks Statistik (2023). <em>Indvandrere i Danmark 2023</em>. <a href="https://www.dst.dk" rel="noopener">www.dst.dk</a></li>
      <li>Udlændinge- og Integrationsministeriet. <em>Lovgivning om integration og udlændinge</em>. <a href="https://www.uim.dk" rel="noopener">www.uim.dk</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
